Title: Mindset: The New Psychology of Success
Author: Carol S. Dweck
My Review: While I think this book has some advice to offer, I have some issues with some of it. For example, even if someone with depression has a growth mindset it doesn't mean they'll be able to get up and get things done. Differences in other factors besides intelligence and hard work don't seem to be taken into consideration. Some are mentioned, but it seemed like they were glossed over. There are also several studies designed to replicate the results of Dweck's study, that haven't shown any significant differences in growth mindset vs. everything else. It's worth the read, but to me, it's just one part of a much more complex whole.

Title: The General's Bride (The Disgraced Martyr Trilogy, #2)
Author: M.F. Sullivan
My Review:
After reading the first book, I expected the second to be similar, but it took me on tangents I never expected while giving me so many new things to think about! The first book is dark, but this one comes in a kaleidoscope of the shades of night. There are sci-fi (and sci-fact!) elements mixed together with dystopian fantasy and mythology. It's a mix that not many authors could pull off, but Sullivan makes it seem easy. There are nymphs, vampires, and saints along with the Mandelbrot set, space travel, and black holes all blended together into a thought-provoking book that touches on topics relevant to us all.

This book, like the first, isn't a fluff book, so if you're looking for something to read that will let you concentrate on other things, don't bother cracking the spine. If, however, you want something dark and deep, then you've come to the right place.

My Review:
I received this book in exchange for a fair and honest review.

This is one of the best books I've read in a long time! It takes on all sorts of issues while delivering an excellent story that hooked me from the first. I'm a sucker for a superhero book, but this book, while about characters with abilities we'd consider superpowers, isn't just about those abilities. It's about humans and compassion and trying to lead a normal life. It's about people who face all forms of prejudice and about trying to figure out who the real monsters are and what you can do about it when you have to face them. I can't wait to read the next one.

Title: The Hierophant's Daughter (The Disgraced Martyr Trilogy, #1)
Author: M.F. Sullivan
My Review:
I received this book in exchange for an honest review.

This is the second book by Sullivan that I've read and enjoyed. The first, The Lightning Stenographer, was much deeper and harder to follow than this one, but worth the effort. This story didn't throw me around as much, and even though it was more violent, didn't feel as dark to me. Of course, dark is a plus as far as I'm concerned, so bear that in mind.

The Heirophant's Daughter takes place in an alternate future and comes complete with a timeline that I didn't notice until I read some of the other reviews. It cleared up quite a few of the gaps in my reading, although I didn't get too confused without it. You do have to carry on reading to understand some of it, but I like to turn those gaps over in my mind to come up with plausible possibilities. When they're explained later (and they are in this book), it just makes all those imaginings even better when they're close to the author's path.

If you're looking for a fun, fluffy read, step away from this book. If you're looking for a new twist on vampires and don't mind putting a little thought into the story, then I highly recommend this one. I'm looking forward to seeing where the next book goes!

Author: Deanna Raybourn
My Review:
Since I started with book 3 in the series, I'll have to go back and read the first two. Reading the third book first, I didn't feel like I was missing anything. There were small things about the relationship that will probably be clearer when I finish the first book, but I didn't feel lost like can happen with other series.

I'm looking forward to the next book to see what happens with Victoria and Stoker. Victoria, with all her intelligence and self-confidence, seems to me to be much more vulnerable than her outward appearance would show. Stoker, however, is my favorite. The encounters with his past in this book showed what a complex character he is.

There were parts of the mystery that I guessed would happen, but there was plenty I didn't see coming. I knew the main villain was the culprit fairly early, but I was wrong about one of the others who turned out to be completely innocent. Overall, it was an entertaining read.

My Review: I love how Sherrilyn Kenyon goes back to the beginnings of the main character in her books to give us the backstory, but I got lost several times with this one. I think it may have been a problem with the audio version. Maybe the book has something to mark where it skips to another part of the story, but there were more than a few times I had to rewind a couple minutes to make sure the action was happening to different characters than a few minutes before. Other than that little blip, however, the book was amazing. I'm loving the direction she's taking the storyline now and I can't wait for the next one.

Title: Sunny with a Chance of Monsters (Sunny Day, Paranormal Badass)
Author: Sara  King
My Review:
I think I've read all Sara King's books and there's a very good reason for that: her books are awesome! She writes across all sorts of genres, but it doesn't matter because it's her characters you fall in love with. This one is what I'd call a mix between sci-fi and urban fantasy with her typical humor baked right in. It has an alternate-history-Alaska crust and chock full of chewy interdimensional monster goodness...sort of like calamari pie.

Read it! You won't be disappointed.

Title: The Stars Now Unclaimed (The Universe After #1)
Author: Drew   Williams
My Review:
I received a copy of this book from NetGalley in exchange for an honest review.

When I was younger, I used to read sci-fi almost exclusively, but now it's more like 6 to 10 titles a year. This book was quite a bit of fun. The author was new to me, so I wasn't sure what to expect - I was pleasantly surprised. The book has lots of action and adventure but manages to throw some awesome characters in the mix, too.

The main character - I won't say her name since you have to get through quite a bit of the book before you know it - was reminiscent of swashbuckling male characters. I always love it when the women get to have the fun! Overall, the book has bits of Hitchhiker's Guide and Firefly, but still manages to be original. I'll be looking out for more by Drew WIlliams after reading this.

Title: In the Mood Fur Love
Author: Eve Langlais
My Review:
I received a copy of this book in exchange for an honest review.

I was familiar with two of the three authors of this book. Eve Langlais will always be one of my favorite favorites. Kate Baxter was new for me and I'm glad I found her!

The first story, Bearing His Touch, by Eve Langlais is definitely just as quirky as all her other stories. There's romance, adventure, but most of all there's humor. It was such a fun read.

The second story, Fake Mated to the Wolf, by Milly Taiden was also similar to her other stories. I think the characters are from another series, but it's not one I've read before. Even so, it was a stand-alone and doesn't depend on reading previous books. It was a fun read, but the name of the main character annoyed me to no end.

The third story, The Witch, the Werewolf, and the Waitress, by Kate Baxter had some new twists that I haven't read before (and I've read LOTS of these stories). I'm going looking for more of her work after reading this story.

Title: To Siri With Love: A Mother, Her Autistic Son, and the Kindness of a Machine
Author: Judith Newman
My Review:
I wanted to read this after seeing how angry it made some people. I really expected it to be more offensive than it was. Yes, there are some things that made me wonder why she said it. For example, calling Amythest Schaber a "manic pixie dream girl." There really was no reason to describe anyone like that...ever! Maybe she didn't mean it in the same sense that Nathan Rabin did, but someone should have caught it before it went to print.

The part about imagining Gus having sex was just creepy. I mean, who wants to imagine their kids (or parents, grandparents, etc.) having sex? Maybe it was meant to be humorous since she compared to Benny Hill and Yakkety Sax. I have no idea what was going on in her head when writing this, but I have to say that, as a parent, it kind of skeeved me out.

From what I understand, the biggest complaint about the book is the author taking about getting medical power of attorney so she can make sure Gus has a vasectomy. This one stumped me. I was furious that she even thought about doing this! After reading more, I'm not so sure what to think. Yes, this reminded me of the whole eugenics movement and literally made me nauseous to read it and think some parent considered this for her child. Later she makes it sound like she'd only do it as a temporary measure (most vasectomies can be reversible these days) to let Gus mature to the point he's ready to be a father. Whether she meant it to be temporary or permanent doesn't really make up for the fact that she considered it.

I can imagine being on the spectrum and reading this book how infuriated I'd be. Autistic people are people, with feelings, hopes, and dreams just like anyone else. Yes, they may see the world in a completely different light than other people, but even so-called neurotypical people can see the world in drastically different ways than other neurotypicals.

This book was written from the point-of-view of a mother, who admits she wasn't even sure she wanted children and ended up with twins. Most parents with autistic children struggle to make sure their child can manage when they're on their own. Hell, most parents struggle with the same thing, no matter how capable their children seem. I'm not particularly happy with some of the ideas the author had, but people should also realize that these are her thoughts and feelings. We all have some of those we act on and others we know won't go further than our heads.

Title: Censored: A Literary History of Subversion and Control
Author: Matthew Fellion
My Review: This is an excellent look at several banned books over the centuries. Each chapter tells the story of a different book that has been censored for various reasons. It has a good balance between going too deep into each story vs. not deeply enough. The best part are all the references for further reading. The research put into this book is incredible and the endnotes (references only, no author notes) are almost as many pages as the story in each chapter.

Title: The Philosopher's Flight (The Philosophers Series, #1)
Author: Tom        Miller
My Review: It's difficult to find new approaches to supernatural stories, but this one managed wonderfully. Those who would be called witches or magicians are instead empirical philosophers. It doesn't quite turn gender dynamics on its head, but having more women in powerful places was refreshing. The author did a great job of making the switch believable and interesting. Of course, there are still those who try to hold back progress, both men and women. I highly recommend this book and I'll keep my eye out for the next one.

Title: Reading with Patrick: A Teacher, a Student, and a Life-Changing Friendship
Author: Michelle  Kuo
My Review:
This book really got to me. I'm a college math instructor and many of my students seem to have the problems of the world on their shoulders. I know that's what all 18 and 19 year-olds think, but that's just their limited view of life. The students I'm talking about are the ones who miss class because their drug-addicted parents kick them out of the house and they either oversleep because they had to sell their phone and watch or they're embarrassed because they only have one outfit to wear and it smells. Even those students have a better deal than the ones in this book.

In the beginning of the book, it's uplifting to see how Ms. Kuo's attention makes such a difference to all the students. They bloom in her class because they finally have someone who cares. I see that happen occasionally in my own classes and it keeps me from being overwhelmed by frustration at not being able to help all my students.

The part that got me was what happens to those same students when she leaves. Maybe all teachers want to believe that they make a difference in someone's life. I know I'm that idealistic and I can't be the only one. The reality is, however, that once they're out of our classroom, they're faced with all the same problems. Sometimes caring just isn't enough.

This book has stayed with me for weeks. On a recent conference trip, I even made a side trip to Helena, Arkansas because I wanted to see where the book takes place. I'm really not even sure why I thought it was important, and after driving around the streets, I'm still not sure. I think I was looking for a way to say that Helena isn't like the towns around mine. If it's smaller, or poorer, or just worse in some way, then my kids would have a better chance - the bloom will stick for some of them.

If you work with kids, read this book. It will change you. It made me realize that I may never be able to change a student's life as dramatically as I'd like. But maybe...just maybe, I can help them see that they can change it themselves. In the end, however, the most important changes will be the ones those students make on my own life.

Title: Shadow Sight (Ivy Granger, #1)
Author: E.J. Stevens
My Review:
It was promising, but ultimately failed to deliver anything. I was annoyed at the beginning when the demon first visits. She's told him no and going to toss holy water on him. He disappears, but leaves a card saying he'll be back tomorrow. What does Ivy do? Plans to meet him! WHY?

The information dumps and constantly telling us every single thought, no matter how irrelevant, running through Ivy's head. And there's repetition of that information, sometimes in the next couple of sentences.

Overall, it just left me saying, "meh." It wasn't terrible, but it wasn't nearly as good as it could have been. I doubt I'll go looking for the second book, but we'll see...

Author: Kresley Cole
My Review:
I don't normally go looking for m/m books, but I don't intentionally skip them either. I know they're not everyone's cup of tea, but I'm sort of ambivalent. This one doesn't seem necessary for the series, but I loved Caspion and Mirceo in the earlier books and wanted to see them get their own HEA. I've always loved Kresley Cole's stories and this one didn't disappoint. There were times I wanted to strangle both the main characters, but books that can make me feel that way towards ANY character are well worth the read.

I'm not sure why people are giving this book a low rating while admitting that they'd never read it. To me, that seems to insult other readers' intelligence. It's right there in the blurb that this book has two males falling in love. Do they think people will read the synopsis and, being undecided, read their rant about how m/m books are gross to decide not to read it? Really? Rating a book without reading it is just childish and not a good look for anyone. Read it or don't, you're not special enough that other people's reading choices are hanging on your every word.

Author: Holger Hoock
My Review: This is not my normal genre of reading material, but the premise sounded interesting and Netgalley let me read it. I thought I might end up reading a bit and then suggesting it to my husband. I ended up reading the entire book and enjoying it, even looking forward to reading it before bed. It may not appeal to a historian or someone who has studied the Revolution in detail, but then again, it might. I can honestly say that it's not written on a level that would go over anyone's head. It's an enthralling read and I recommend it to those just getting started or who has studied the Revolution for a while.

Title: Our Only Chance (A.I. Chronicles #1)
Author: Ray Else
My Review:
I got this book thinking it might be somewhat interesting. Considering I couldn't put it down after I was past the halfway point, I'd say it managed to be much more than 'somewhat interesting.' I stayed up all night reading because I just had to see what happened next, and as someone who loves to sleep even more than I love to read, that's high praise indeed.

I'd never heard of the author before this book was recommended to me on Netgalley, but the blurb sounded interesting and I'd just finished a book, so I figured I'd give it a try. Many self-published books have too many errors for me to get through the entire book, no matter how good the story could be. This book, thankfully, wasn't like that. The timing was great, the characters were extremely well-developed, and the storytelling was amazing. Even though I could see glimmers of what might happen at the end, it still surprised me. You knew the ending was going to contain certain elements, but trying to see how those elements would come together was what kept me reading all night. All in all, this was an excellent book and I recommend it to anyone interested in thinking about what direction our technology is going to take and how that's going to affect what is is that makes us human.

Title: Owl and the Japanese Circus (Adventures of Owl, #1)
Author: Kristi Charish
My Review:
I didn't love the book, but I didn't hate it either. Owl didn't really do it for me like a heroine should. She was a bit two-dimensional, while some of the other characters (Oricho and Nadya) stood out.

It didn't help that in the first chapter she says that she took a Japanese artifact out from under a team of archaeologists working on the Terracotta Warrior site. Why did that bother me? The Terracotta warriors are CHINESE! What's an artifact from Japan doing in China? Since it was never explained and Owl said it like it was nothing, I'm going to assume that the author didn't do any research at all before throwing that in.

I also have a hard time reading about someone who takes artifacts from their sites for profit. Maybe it's because I have an anthropology background, but I had to keep reminding myself that it was just a book. Still, I can't read/watch Curious George to this day and my kids and grandkids don't watch it either.

That said, I'm still going to listen to the second book. It's mostly because I'm curious about Carpe and I want to see if Oricho pops back up.

Author: Kym Grosso
My Review: I listened to the audio version of the story. The narrator was good, but the story itself could have been much better. Sydney's actions and reactions were totally unbelievable and Kade's character just seemed flat. And could someone please take the thesaurus away from the author? I mean, she has the female lead 'calcitrate' her legs. Without context or a dictionary, how many people know what that is? Just say she kicked for goodness sake! Of course, there was also my favorite - Sydney descended her arm. She meant that Sydney lowered her arm, but what she said is that Sydney climbed down her own arm. I have a great imagination, but even I have trouble picturing anyone but a contortionist pulling that one off.

Title: Embrace the Dark (The Blood Rose, #1)
Author: Caris Roane
My Review:
I really liked this story. The writing, however, ruined it for me and I found it hard to finish reading it. There were just so many weird wordings and editing mistakes that took too much away from what could have been an excellent novella. For example, after the main couple's first time together, Abigail "sighed over and over." That sounds, at least to me, like she was more disappointed than content. After Gerrod had been taken by the Invictus, Gus comes to tell Abigail what's happened. Keep in mind that Gus seems to adore Gerrod and would understandably be upset about him being in enemy hands. Yet, he only gives a 'recital' to explain everything to Abigail like he isn't really feeling anything at all.
The world-building was a bit thin, but that can be overlooked for a novella in a series. I may give the second book in the series a try to see if the writing/editing improves. Especially since I've heard and read such good things about Caris Roane's books.

Title: The Shape of Desire (Shifting Circle, #1)
Author: Sharon Shinn
My Review: I've read other Sharon Shinn books and they were fantastic. This one was just boring. I started it several times and had to make myself finish it. Most of the story was Maria talking about her undying devotion to Dante, even if he just happened to be killing people while in his animal form. I have to say that I think Ellen's character was much easier to like than Maria and Will seemed more interesting than Dante. Reading more about Will would be the only reason I read the second book in the series. I'll definitely try more of Sharon Shinn's books, however, since one of her other series is a favorite.

My Review:
Even though I've loved this series from the first book, I was almost afraid to read this one. It seemed like Gray and Dillon wouldn't have much of a romance left to write since their romance has teased us from the first book. I have to admit (gladly) that my fears were unfounded. This book builds beautifully on the first three and brings more in for future stories.

The ending was the perfect lead in to the next story and I can't wait to read it! I've been hoping that the mutore would get their own stories and it looks like I get my wish.

If you like hot PNR, then I highly recommend this series (this was the hottest so far). Don't get it if you're easily offended by graphic sex scenes with crude language (especially this particular book).

Title: Deadlocked (Sookie Stackhouse, #12)
Author: Charlaine Harris
My Review:
I lost heart with this series with books 9 and 10, but the last two have restored my faith. I've always been pretty ambivalent about Sookie's love interest (except for the book that had Eric under a spell) as long as it wasn't Bill. I've just never warmed up to him as a character; he always seems a bit flat to me. With this book, I can see that Eric and Sookie aren't meant to be and I'm really curious what's going to happen after this ending has her saving Sam instead of wishing for Eric to stay with her.

The story in this book was excellent as well. There were plenty of twists and turns and I didn't expect some of them at all. This was one of my favorite books in this series and I'm simultaneously looking forward to and dreading the last book.

Author: Lisa Renee Jones
My Review:
It wasn't a bad book(s), but it could have been better. It makes for a fantastic draft of a book that needs a bit more development and editing. If you're the type that gets really annoyed with editing problems, then you might want to hold off on this one.

The stories were good, but again, could have done with more development. Especially with Kelly (2nd story) promising to help Aiden fix Troy and then both of them disappearing. Kelly never shows back up, but Aiden comes in at the very end.

I enjoyed the story, but it was like reading a draft for a final book instead of the finished product.

Title: My Name Is Memory
Author: Ann Brashares
My Review:
I loved this book, but I'm worried there won't be a sequel. Evidently it started out as the first in a trilogy, but there are some problems with the publisher. That's the only reason it didn't get five stars.

I listened to the audio, so I didn't notice any editing errors. Funny how that whole OCD/grammar police thing goes out the window when the story comes through the ears instead of the eyes.

The idea of someone remembering all their past lives is fascinating and I really enjoyed the stories of Daniel's lifetimes. My only wish would be for the ending NOT to be a cliff-hanger. But again, it was supposed to be the first of three and it so it would all be resolved later. If the second book comes out, the rating may get an update. Keeping my fingers crossed.

Title: Violet Tendencies (Sabina Kane, #2.5)
Author: Jaye Wells
My Review: Short, but now I know what happened to Valva and what's going on when they talk about the strip club.

Title: Killing Rites (The Black Sun's Daughter, #4)
Author: M.L.N. Hanover
My Review:
Again, this series just keeps getting better. But maybe that's because I've always had a soft spot for Ex. This book gives us a real insight into where Ex comes from. Jayne is, of course, dealing with everything from the last book as well as the new crisis.

Overall, this is my favorite book from the series and I hope the trend continues.

Title: Vicious Grace (The Black Sun's Daughter, #3)
Author: M.L.N. Hanover
My Review:
The series keeps getting better! We get to see the characters developed a bit more and I'm glad to see Aubrey go. I guess some may like him, but his character seems a bit wimpy in my opinion. The internment and its repercussions made the book for me. Not because I enjoyed the internment, but because it showed that life isn't all fluff and stuff. Sometimes you just have to do something you didn't think you ever could to protect humanity.

The feel for this book is starting to remind me of Kim Harrison's Rachel Morgan series. The worlds aren't similar, but there's a darkness, or maybe a melancholy, to the main character.

Title: Darker Angels (The Black Sun's Daughter, #2)
Author: M.L.N. Hanover
My Review:
This is the second in the series and sees Jayne and the gang in New Orleans. While not obvious, the twist wasn't a huge surprise either. Still, I liked this book better than the first in the series. I felt like I got to know the characters a bit better (still not much insight into Ex yet) and I think I just liked the story a bit better. Others may disagree, but that's my take on it.

Overall, better than the first in the series and the last words have me anxious to get started on the third book.

Title: Unclean Spirits (The Black Sun's Daughter, #1)
Author: M.L.N. Hanover
My Review:
M.L.N. Hanover has come up with a new take on the paranormal creature scene. We still have vampires and werewolves along with lots of other categories of beasties, but they're separate entities, called riders by the main characters, who inhabit humans. I really enjoyed the book - enough to go buy the rest of the series, but it didn't jump to the top of my favorite series list. Of course, I tend to prefer more humor. Another thing that bothered me was the almost non-existent sex scene. It reminded me of an old movie where there's enough innuendo to know what's going on, but no steam. I'm not one to insist on graphic sex, but something a bit less bland than 'we went through two condoms' please. I'm not sure if that's exactly what was said, but you get the general idea.

The characters are very interesting and have as much development as most in the first book of a series. You get an idea of where they all are coming from (except for Ex), and what makes them tick. I can't say anything about editing since I listened to the audio book and I don't catch mistakes through my ears unless they're glaringly obvious.

Overall, I'd recommend this book to anyone who enjoys PNR or UF.
